stry.com/news/first-foundation-nordsee-one-successfully First foundation for Nordsee One successfully installed</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thorntonbank Wind Farm|Thorntonbank <br/> (phases 1\u20133)]] || 325 || {{BEL}} || {{coord|51|33|00|N|2|56|00|E |type:landmark_region:BE |name=Thorntonbank phases 1&2&3}} || 6 \u00d7 [[Senvion]] 5MW<br /> 48 \u00d7 Senvion 6.15MW || 2009 (phase 1)<br />2012 (phase 2)<br />2013 (phase 3)||<ref name=\"C-Power: General Informations\">[http://www.c-power.be/English/welcome/algemene_info.html C-Power: General Informations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423030705/http://www.c-power.be/English/welcome/algemene_info.html |date=2012-04-23 }}</ref><ref name=\"rwe.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rwe.com/web/cms/en/86182/rwe-innogy/news-press/press/?pmid=4006424|title=RWE Innogy - Press release 09 July 2013 Export cables in at Gwynt y M\u00f4r Offshore Wind Farm|work=rwe.com|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repower.de/press/press-releases/detail-press/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=8109&cHash=071ef77c45bd3f13dc55372ca3c95111|title=Phase 2 completed|author=|first=|date=|website=RePower - All the energy you need|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"offshorewind.biz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.offshorewind.biz/2013/09/18/belgium-thornton-bank-offshore-wind-farm-officially-inaugurated/|title=Belgium: Thornton Bank Offshore Wind Farm Officially Inaugurated|work=Offshore Wind|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=2013-09-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sheringham Shoal Offshore Wind Farm|Sheringham Shoal]] || 315 || {{GBR}} || {{coord|53|7|0|N|1|8|0|E |type:landmark_region:GB |name=Sheringham Shoal Offshore Wind Farm}} || 88 \u00d7 Siemens SWT-3.6-107 || 2012 ||<ref name=\"siemens_3.6_107\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.powergeneration.siemens.com/products-solutions-services/products-packages/wind-turbines/products/swt-3-6-107/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725000136/http://www.powergeneration.siemens.com/products-solutions-services/products-packages/wind-turbines/products/swt-3-6-107/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-07-25 |title=SWT-3.6-107 Wind Turbine |publisher=[[Siemens]] |accessdate=2009-07-19 }}</ref><ref name=\"sheringham_shoal_fact_sheet\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.statoilhydro.com/en/TechnologyInnovation/NewEnergy/RenewablePowerProduction/Offshore/SheringhamShoel/Downloads/Fact%20sheet.pdf | title=Sheringham Shoal Offshore Wind Farm |publisher=[[StatoilHydro]]|accessdate=2009-07-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scira.co.uk/|title=Sheringham Shoal Operated by Statkraft|author=Trickyweb|first=|date=2015|work=SHERINGHAM SHOAL, Offshore Wind Farm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.offshorewind.biz/2012/09/27/norways-crown-prince-opens-sheringham-shoal-offshore-wind-farm-uk/|title=Norway's Crown Prince Opens Sheringham Shoal Offshore Wind Farm (UK)|work=Offshore Wind|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=2012-09-27}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{interlanguage link|Borkum Riffgrund Wind Farm|lt=Borkum Riffgrund 1|de|Offshore-Windpark Borkum Riffgrund}} || 312 || {{DEU}} || {{coord|53|58|0|N|06|33|00|E |type:landmark_region:DE |name=Borkum Riffgrund 1 Wind Farm}} || 78 \u00d7 Siemens SWT-4.0-120 || 2015 ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/borkum-riffgrund-i-germany-de04.html|title=Borkum Riffgrund I|work=4coffshore.com|accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Amrumbank West]]\n|302\n|{{DEU}}\n|{{coord|54|30|0|N|07|48|00|E|type:landmark_region:DE|name=Amrumbank West Wind Farm}}\n|80 x Siemens SWT-3.6-120\n|2015\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/amrumbank-west-germany-de05.html|title=Amrumbank West - 4C Offshore|website=www.4coffshore.com|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thanet Offshore Wind Project|Thanet]] || 300 || {{GBR}} || {{coord|51|26|0|N|01|38|0|E |type:landmark_region:GB |name=Thanet Offshore Wind Project}} || 100 \u00d7 [[Vestas]] V90-3.0MW || 2010 ||<ref>{{Cite web |title=Thanet |publisher=The Engineer Online |date=2008-07-25 |url=http://www.theengineer.co.uk/Articles/308825/Wind+farm+project.htm |accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Thanet offshore wind farm starts electricity production |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-11395824 |date=2010-09-23 |accessdate=2010-09-30 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Projects===\nMost of the current projects are in European and East Asian waters.\n\nThere are also several proposed developments in North America.\nProjects are under development in the United States in wind-rich areas of the East Coast, Great Lakes, and Pacific coast. \nIn January 2012, a \"Smart for the Start\" regulatory approach was introduced, designed to expedite the siting process while incorporating strong environmental protections. \nSpecifically, the Department of Interior approved \u201cwind energy areas\u201d off the coast where projects can move through the regulatory approval process more quickly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2012/02/offshore-wind-one-step-closer-to-reality-in-the-mid-atlantic |title=Offshore Wind One Step Closer to Reality in the Mid-Atlantic |author=Kit Kennedy |date=2 February 2012 |work=Renewable Energy World }}</ref> \nThe first offshore wind farm in the USA is the 30-megawatt, 5 turbine [[Block Island Wind Farm]] which was commissioned in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121774/offshore-wind-farm-first-us |title= America Is Finally Getting Its First Offshore Wind Farm. Conservatives Are Trying to Make Sure It's the Last. |work=New Republic |date=14 May 2015 |accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://dwwind.com/project/block-island-wind-farm/ |title=Block Island Wind Farm - Deepwater Wind|work=Deepwater Wind|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> Another offshore wind farm that is in the planning phase is off the coast of [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]]. On August 3, 2018, [[Dominion Energy]] announced its two wind turbine pilot program that will be 27 miles offshore from Virginia Beach. The area is undergoing a survey that will last for 4\u20136 weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.13newsnow.com/article/news/local/mycity/virginia-beach/offshore-wind-energy-heading-to-waters-off-virginia-beach/291-580260639|title=Offshore wind energy heading to waters off Virginia Beach|work=WVEC|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nCanadian wind power in the province of Ontario is pursuing several proposed locations in the [[Great Lakes]], including the suspended<ref name=\"noTril\">[http://www.albertaoilmagazine.com/2011/04/gamed/ Offshore wind development hits a snag in Ontario] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109073822/http://www.albertaoilmagazine.com/2011/04/gamed/ |date=2012-01-09 }} ''Alberta Oil Magazine'', April 2011. Accessed: 29 September 2011.</ref> [[Trillium Power Wind 1]] approximately 20&nbsp;km from shore and over 400&nbsp;MW in capacity.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/article/294044|title = Ontario to approve Great Lakes wind power|date = January 15, 2008 |accessdate = 2008-05-02 | work=The Star | location=Toronto | first=Tyler | last=Hamilton}}</ref> \nOther Canadian projects include one on the Pacific west coast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.naikun.ca/index.php|title = Naikun Wind Development, Inc.|accessdate = 2008-05-21}}</ref>\n\nIndia is looking at the potential of offshore wind power plants, with a 100 MW demonstration plant being planned off the coast of [[Gujarat]] (2014).<ref>{{cite web|title=MOU Signed for First Ever Offshore Wind Power Project in India|url= http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=110186 |website=www.pib.nic.in |publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India|accessdate=30 April 2015|date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, a group of organizations, led by [[Global Wind Energy Council|Global Wind Energy Council (GWEC)]] started project [[FOWIND]] (Facilitating Offshore Wind in India) to identify potential zones for development of off-shore wind power in India and to stimulate R & D activities in this area. In 2014 FOWIND commissioned [[Center for Study of Science, Technology and Policy (CSTEP)]] to undertake pre-feasibility studies in eight zones in Tamil Nadu which have been identified as having potential.<ref>{{cite news|author1=R. Srikanth|author2=Sangeetha Kandavel|title=Tapping the offshore wind|url= http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tapping-the-offshore-wind/article6833433.ece |accessdate=30 April 2015|agency=The Hindu|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Offshore wind power by country==\n[[File:DanishWindTurbines.jpg|thumb|500px|Offshore wind turbines near [[Copenhagen]], Denmark]]\nMost of offshore wind farms are currently in northern Europe. \nThe United Kingdom and Germany alone accounted for roughly two thirds of the total offshore wind power capacity installed worldwide in 2016.\nOther countries, such as China, are rapidly expanding their offshore wind power capacity.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+List of countries by cumulative installed offshore wind power capacity (MW)<ref name=\"gwec2017\">{{cite web|url=https://gwec.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/GWEC-Global-Wind-Report-2018.pdf|title=Global Wind Report 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=gwec.net|publisher=Global Wind Energy Council (GWEC)|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! Rank || Country || 2016 || 2017\n!2018\n|-\n| 1 || [[List of offshore wind farms in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] || 5,156 || 6,651\n|7,963\n|-\n| 2 || [[List of offshore wind farms in Germany|Germany]] || 4,108 || 5,411\n|6,380\n|-\n| 3 || [[List of offshore wind farms in China|China]] || 1,627 || 2,788\n|4,588\n|-\n| 4 || [[List of offshore wind farms in Denmark|Denmark]] || 1,271 || 1,268\n|1,329\n|-\n|5\n|[[List of offshore wind farms in Belgium|Belgium]]\n|712\n|877\n|1,186\n|-\n| 6 || [[List of offshore wind farms in the Netherlands|Netherlands]]|| 1,118 || 1,118\n|1,118\n|-\n| 7 || [[List of offshore wind farms in Sweden|Sweden]] || 202 || 202\n|192\n|-\n| 8 || Vietnam || 99 || 99\n|99\n|-\n|9\n|South Korea\n|35\n|38\n|73\n|-\n| 10 || Finland || 32 || 92\n|87\n|-\n| 11 ||[[List of offshore wind farms in Japan|Japan]]|| 60 || 65\n|65\n|-\n| 12 || [[List of offshore wind farms in the United States|United States]] || 30 || 30\n|30\n|-\n| 13 || Ireland || 25 || 25\n|25\n|-\n| 14 || Taiwan || 0 || 8\n|8\n|-\n| 15 || Spain || 5 || 5\n|5\n|-\n| 16 || Norway || 2 || 2\n|2\n|-\n| 17 || France|| 0 || 2\n|2\n|-\n! || World total || 14,482 || 18,658 || 23,140\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category}}\n*[[List of offshore wind farms]]\n*[[Lists of offshore wind farms by water area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{wind power}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Wind power]]\n", "name_user": "StYxXx", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFuture development:+[[]]", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offshore_wind_power"}
{"title_page": "Olaf Storaasli", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Olaf Storaasli\n| image = Olaf O. Storaasli photo (Manchester UK).jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|05|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| website=\n| alam_mater=\n| occupation = Computational Science & Engineering\n}}\n\n'''Olaf O. Storaasli''', [http://www.synective.se Synective Labs] VP, was a researcher at [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]] (Computer Science and Mathematics Division's [http://www.csm.ornl.gov/PR/PR2005/hpc-09-09-05_2.html Future Technologies Group]) and [[USEC]] following his [[NASA Langley Research Center|NASA]] career. He led the hardware, software and applications teams' successful development of one of NASA's 1st parallel computers, the [[Finite element machine]] and developed rapid matrix equation algorithms tailored to high-performance computers (even harnessing [[FPGA]] accelerators) to solve science and engineering applications. He was PhD advisor and graduate instructor at [[University of Tennessee|UT]], [[George Washington University|GWU]] and [[Christopher Newport University|CNU]] and mentored 25 [[New Horizons Governor's School for Science and Technology|NHGS]] students. He is recognized by [[American Men and Women of Science]], [[Marquis Who's Who]], and [[NASA]], [[Cray]], [[Intel]] and [http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/pplnews_OlafStoraasli.html Concordia College] awards. NASA Awards include [[Viking program|Viking]] Mars Lander design and Engineering Analysis ([https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19850017910.pdf IPAD], [[R:Base|RIM]], [[Supercomputing|HPC]], [[FPGA]], SPAR, [[Finite element machine|FEM]], [[Space Shuttle]] [[Solid Rocket Booster|SRB]] and [http://73.108.22.21:8080/~olaf/OS/www/syaward.html NASA Software-of-the-year]).\n\n==Education==\n\nStoraasli received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Physics, Mathematics & French ([[Concordia College (Moorhead)|Concordia College]], 1964), [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in [[Mathematics]] ([[University of South Dakota|USD]],1966), [[Ph.D]] in [[Engineering Mechanics]] ([[North Carolina State University|NCSU]], 1970) and post-doc fellowships: [[Norwegian University of Science & Technology|NTNU]] ([http://73.121.39.212:8080/~olaf/OS/www/nasa/Thompson.jpg 1984\u201385]), [[University of Edinburgh]] ([http://73.121.39.212:8081/~olaf/OS/www/pubs/EPCCNews08.pdf 2008]).\n\n==Research==\nHe develops, tests and documents [[Parallel Computing|parallel]] analysis software to speed [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] equation solution to simulate physical & biological behavior on advanced-computer architectures (e.g. NASA's [https://www.hq.nasa.gov/hpcc/reports/annrpt97/accomps/cas_larc/WW60.html GPS] solver based on prior [[Finite element machine]] and rapid parallel analysis of [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster|Space Shuttle SRB]] redesign earned [[Cray|Cray's]] 1st GigaFLOP Performance [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/olafva/srb.jpg Award] at Supercomputing '89).\n\n==[http://73.121.39.212:8081/~olaf/OS/www/pubs/Books/ Books]==\n* Engineering Applications on NASA's FPGA-based Hypercomputer, 7th MAPLD, Washington, D.C., Sept 2004.\n* Large-Scale Analysis, Design and Intelligent Synthesis Environments, Elsevier Sciences, 2000.\n* Large-Scale Analysis & Design on High-Performance Computers & Workstations, Elsevier Sciences, 1998.\n* Large-Scale Structural Analysis for High-Performance Computers & Workstations, Pergamon Press 1994.\n* Parallel Computational Methods for Large-Scale Structural Analysis & Design, Pergamon Press 1993.\n* Parallel Methods on Large-Scale Structural Analysis & Physics Applications, Pergamon Press 1991.\n\n==References==\n1 [http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=96634 Olaf Storaasli] at the [[Mathematics Genealogy Project]]<br>\n2 [http://babrodtk.at.ifi.uio.no/files/publications/brodtkorb_etal_star_heterocomp.pdf State-of-the-Art in Heterogeneous Computing], Scientific Programming 18 pp.&nbsp;1\u201333, IOS Press, 2010.(+PARA10)<br>\n3 [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=4531732&count=13&index=2&tag=1&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Fisnumber%3D4670333%26arnumber%3D4531732%26count%3D13%26index%3D2%26tag%3D1 High-Performance Mixed-Precision Linear Solver for FPGAs], IEEE Trans Computers 57/12, 1614\u20131623, 2008.<br>\n4 Accelerating Science Applications up to 100X with FPGAs, PARA08 Proc.Trondheim Norway, May 2008.<br>\n5 [https://www.academia.edu/30776575/Computational_Speed-Up_of_Complex_Durability_Analysis_of_Large-Scale_Composite_Structures Computation Speed-up of Complex Durability Analysis of Large-Scale Composite Structures], AIAA 49th SDM Proc. 2008.<br>\n6 [https://private.ecit.qub.ac.uk/MSRC/Wednesday_Abstracts/Storaasli_OakRidge.pdf Accelerating Genome Sequencing 100-1000X] MRSC Proc. Queen's University, Belfast, UK April 1\u20133, 2008.<br>\n7 [https://www.osti.gov/scitech/biblio/931879 Exploring Accelerating Science Applications with FPGAs], NCSA/RSSI Proc. Urbana, IL, July 20, 2007.<br>\n8 [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.96.6844&rep=rep1&type=pdf Performance Evaluation of FPGA-Based Biological Applications], Cray Users Group Proc. Seattle, May 2007.<br>\n9 [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=4297292&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Farnumber%3D4297292 Sparse Matrix-Vector Multiplication Design on FPGAs], IEEE 15th Symp on FCCM Proc., 349\u2013352, 2007.<br>\n10 Computing at the Speed of Thought, Aerospace America pp.&nbsp;35\u201338, Oct. 2004.<br>\n11 [http://lawrepository.ualr.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1355&context=appellatepracticeprocess Preface: A Computational Scientist's Perspective on Appellate Technology], 15 J. App. Prac. & Process 39-46 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://insidehpc.com/2009/03/09/ballad-of-the-massively-parallel-supercomputing-pioneers Intel Supercomputing Pioneers] [http://insidehpc.com/images/03092009/MassivelyParallelSupercomputingPioneers.mp3 (song)]\n* [https://thestarphoenix.com/life/bridges/from-brunskill-school-to-mars-dream-big From Brunskill to Mars].\n* [http://olaftn.com/NASA/Learned.html NASA Lessons Learned].\n* [http://olaftn.com Web page].\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=2Uv73X0AAAAJ&hl=en Google Scholar].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Storaasli, Olaf}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Oak Ridge National Laboratory people]]\n[[Category:History of Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Olaf Storaasli\n| image = Olaf O. Storaasli photo (Manchester UK).jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|05|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| website=\n| alam_mater=\n| occupation = Computational Science & Engineering\n}}\n\n'''Olaf O. Storaasli''', [http://www.synective.se Synective Labs] VP, was a researcher at [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]] (Computer Science and Mathematics Division's [http://www.csm.ornl.gov/PR/PR2005/hpc-09-09-05_2.html Future Technologies Group]) and [[USEC]] following his [[NASA Langley Research Center|NASA]] career. He led the hardware, software and applications teams' successful development of one of NASA's 1st parallel computers, the [[Finite element machine]] and developed rapid matrix equation algorithms tailored to high-performance computers (even harnessing [[FPGA]] accelerators) to solve science and engineering applications. He was PhD advisor and graduate instructor at [[University of Tennessee|UT]], [[George Washington University|GWU]] and [[Christopher Newport University|CNU]] and mentored 25 [[New Horizons Governor's School for Science and Technology|NHGS]] students. He is recognized by [[American Men and Women of Science]], [[Marquis Who's Who]], and [[NASA]], [[Cray]], [[Intel]] and [http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/pplnews_OlafStoraasli.html Concordia College] awards. NASA Awards include [[Viking program|Viking]] Mars Lander design and Engineering Analysis ([https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19850017910.pdf IPAD], [[R:Base|RIM]], [[Supercomputing|HPC]], [[FPGA]], SPAR, [[Finite element machine|FEM]], [[Space Shuttle]] [[Solid Rocket Booster|SRB]] and [http://73.108.22.21:8080/~olaf/OS/www/syaward.html NASA Software-of-the-year]).\n\n==Education==\n\nStoraasli received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Physics, Mathematics & French ([[Concordia College (Moorhead)|Concordia College]], 1964), [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in [[Mathematics]] ([[University of South Dakota|USD]],1966), [[Ph.D]] in [[Engineering Mechanics]] ([[North Carolina State University|NCSU]], 1970) and post-doc fellowships: [[Norwegian University of Science & Technology|NTNU]] ([http://73.121.39.212:8080/~olaf/OS/www/nasa/Thompson.jpg 1984\u201385]), [[University of Edinburgh]] ([http://73.121.39.212:8081/~olaf/OS/www/pubs/EPCCNews08.pdf 2008]).\n\n==Research==\nHe develops, tests and documents [[Parallel Computing|parallel]] analysis software to speed [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] equation solution to simulate physical & biological behavior on advanced-computer architectures (e.g. NASA's [https://www.hq.nasa.gov/hpcc/reports/annrpt97/accomps/cas_larc/WW60.html GPS] solver based on prior [[Finite element machine]] and rapid parallel analysis of [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster|Space Shuttle SRB]] redesign earned [[Cray|Cray's]] 1st GigaFLOP Performance [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/olafva/srb.jpg Award] at Supercomputing '89).\n\n==[http://73.121.39.212:8081/~olaf/OS/www/pubs/Books/ Books]==\n* Engineering Applications on NASA's FPGA-based Hypercomputer, 7th MAPLD, Washington, D.C., Sept 2004.\n* Large-Scale Analysis, Design and Intelligent Synthesis Environments, Elsevier Sciences, 2000.\n* Large-Scale Analysis & Design on High-Performance Computers & Workstations, Elsevier Sciences, 1998.\n* Large-Scale Structural Analysis for High-Performance Computers & Workstations, Pergamon Press 1994.\n* Parallel Computational Methods for Large-Scale Structural Analysis & Design, Pergamon Press 1993.\n* Parallel Methods on Large-Scale Structural Analysis & Physics Applications, Pergamon Press 1991.\n\n==References==\n1 [http://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=96634 Olaf Storaasli] at the [[Mathematics Genealogy Project]]<br>\n2 [http://babrodtk.at.ifi.uio.no/files/publications/brodtkorb_etal_star_heterocomp.pdf State-of-the-Art in Heterogeneous Computing], Scientific Programming 18 pp.&nbsp;1\u201333, IOS Press, 2010.(+PARA10)<br>\n3 [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=4531732&count=13&index=2&tag=1&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Fisnumber%3D4670333%26arnumber%3D4531732%26count%3D13%26index%3D2%26tag%3D1 High-Performance Mixed-Precision Linear Solver for FPGAs], IEEE Trans Computers 57/12, 1614\u20131623, 2008.<br>\n4 Accelerating Science Applications up to 100X with FPGAs, PARA08 Proc.Trondheim Norway, May 2008.<br>\n5 [https://www.academia.edu/30776575/Computational_Speed-Up_of_Complex_Durability_Analysis_of_Large-Scale_Composite_Structures Computation Speed-up of Complex Durability Analysis of Large-Scale Composite Structures], AIAA 49th SDM Proc. 2008.<br>\n6 [https://private.ecit.qub.ac.uk/MSRC/Wednesday_Abstracts/Storaasli_OakRidge.pdf Accelerating Genome Sequencing 100-1000X] MRSC Proc. Queen\u2019s University, Belfast, UK April 1\u20133, 2008.<br>\n7 [https://www.osti.gov/scitech/biblio/931879 Exploring Accelerating Science Applications with FPGAs], NCSA/RSSI Proc. Urbana, IL, July 20, 2007.<br>\n8 [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.96.6844&rep=rep1&type=pdf Performance Evaluation of FPGA-Based Biological Applications], Cray Users Group Proc. Seattle, May 2007.<br>\n9 [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=4297292&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Farnumber%3D4297292 Sparse Matrix-Vector Multiplication Design on FPGAs], IEEE 15th Symp on FCCM Proc., 349-352, 2007.<br>\n10 Computing at the Speed of Thought, Aerospace America pp.&nbsp;35\u201338, Oct. 2004.<br>\n11 [http://lawrepository.ualr.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1355&context=appellatepracticeprocess Preface: A Computational Scientist's Perspective on Appellate Technology], 15 J. App. Prac. & Process 39-46 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://insidehpc.com/2009/03/09/ballad-of-the-massively-parallel-supercomputing-pioneers Intel Supercomputing Pioneers] [http://insidehpc.com/images/03092009/MassivelyParallelSupercomputingPioneers.mp3 (song)]\n* [https://thestarphoenix.com/life/bridges/from-brunskill-school-to-mars-dream-big From Brunskill to Mars].\n* [http://olaftn.com/NASA/Learned.html NASA Lessons Learned].\n* [http://olaftn.com Web page].\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=2Uv73X0AAAAJ&hl=en Google Scholar].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Storaasli, Olaf}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Oak Ridge National Laboratory people]]\n[[Category:History of Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 349-352 \u2192 349\u2013352", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olaf_Storaasli"}
{"title_page": "Techonomy Media", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name  = Techonomy Media, Inc.\n| logo  = TechonomyMediaLogo.jpg\n| type  = [[Privately held]]\n| foundation   = [[New York, New York|New York]], [[United States]] ({{Start date|2011}})<ref name=NYC>{{cite web | url= http://appext20.dos.ny.gov/corp_public/CORPSEARCH.ENTITY_INFORMATION?p_nameid=4062629&p_corpid=4060088&p_entity_name=%74%65%63%68%6F%6E%6F%6D%79&p_name_type=%41&p_search_type=%42%45%47%49%4E%53&p_srch_results_page=0| title=NYS Division of Corporations, State Records, & UCC - Corporation Search Results: TECHONOMY MEDIA, INC. | publisher=New York Department of State | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref>\n| founder   = [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]]<ref name=CNET1>{{cite web | url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-20005803-56.html| title=Ex-Fortune trio aims to spark new dialogue | publisher=CNET | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref>\n| location_city   = [[New York, New York]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| key_people  = David Kirkpatrick (CEO)<br>Simone Ross (EVP, Chief Program Officer)<br>Josh Kampel (President)<ref name=\"CNET1\" />\n| industry    = [[Internet]], [[Electronic media|Media]], [[Business conference|Conference]]s\n| products    =\n| num_employees =\n| homepage    = [http://www.techonomy.com Techonomy Media, Inc.]\n}}\n[[File:2010 08 04 techonomy 037 (4863119017).jpg|thumb|right|Techonomy 2010]]\n'''Techonomy Media Inc.''' is an American conference and media company founded in 2011 and headquartered in New York, NY.<ref name=NYC /><ref name=\"CrunchBase\">[http://www.crunchbase.com/company/techonomy-media]</ref> Techonomy organizes the annual invitation-only thought leadership Techonomy conference, which focuses on how the accelerating advancement of technology is transforming business and can help address the world's pressing needs.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=138258679| title=Businessweek Company Overview of Techonomy Media, Inc.| publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref> It is led by [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]], a former technology editor of [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]].<ref name=\"CNET1\" /> Business and tech executives such as [[Bill Gates]] of [[Microsoft]], and [[Ray Kurzweil]] and [[Eric Schmidt]] of [[Google]] have all participated.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url=http://www.freep.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130619/BUSINESS06/306180101/Techonomy-and-Gilbert-and-Twitter| title=Twitter founder returns to headline Techonomy Detroit conference| publisher=Detroit Free Press | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite web | url= https://www.cnbc.com/id/38565740| title=Google's Eric Schmidt Kicks Off 'Techonomy' Conference| publisher=CNBC | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07E6DC1730F930A2575AC0A9669D8B63| title=BITS; Second Thoughts On Web Classes| work=New York Times | accessdate=2013-07-01| first=Steve| last=Lohr| date=2010-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aJatOkKzDi8I| title=Techonomy, LLC, Launches Media Business; Announces Inaugural| publisher=Bloomberg | accessdate=2013-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/techonomy/techonomy-artificial-intelligence_b_2117112.html| title=Kurzweil at Techonomy: Artificial Intelligence Is Empowering All of Humanity| publisher=Huffington Post | accessdate=2013-07-16| date=2012-11-12}}</ref> Its current advisory board consists of [[Marc Benioff]] of [[Salesforce.com]], [[Jack Dorsey]] of [[Twitter]] and [[Square, Inc.|Square]], [[Reid Hoffman]] of [[LinkedIn]], and [[Padmasree Warrior]] of [[Cisco]], among others.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://techonomy.com/manifesto/advisory-board/| title=Techonomy Advisory Board| accessdate=2013-07-09}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nTechonomy's name combines \"technology\" and \"economy\" to suggest that technology is entwined with society. The company's events and media generally argue that tech, if applied productively, can result in tremendous social progress. The company's programs discuss how businesses in almost every industry are faced with the choice of adapting to take advantage of technology or being rendered extinct as the pace of change quickens.<ref name=\"CNBC\"/><ref>Fried, Ina. \"[http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-20005803-56.html Ex-Fortune trio aims to spark new dialogue].\" CNET. Retrieved 9 July 2013.</ref>\n\nThe first Techonomy conference, in 2010, was organized by a partnership that included Kirkpatrick along with former Fortune editors Peter Petre and Brent Schlender, as well as Michael Christman and Carrie Van Heyst.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://venturebeat.com/2010/05/25/fortune-editors-launch-techonomy-a-media-company-that-preaches-technology-can-solve-all-ills/| title=Fortune editors launch Techonomy, a media company that preaches technology can solve all ills | publisher=VentureBeat | accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://eon.businesswire.com/news/eon/20100525005843/en| title=Techonomy, LLC, Launches Media Business; Announces Inaugural Conference; HP, McKinsey, Chevron and Intel are Sponsors| publisher=EON | accessdate=2013-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/business/van-heyst-group-aims-to-turn-company-events-into-media-gold.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0| title=Mining the Power (and the Profit) of Conversation| work=New York Times | accessdate=2013-07-16| first=Christine| last=Larson| date=2012-09-15}}</ref> Techonomy Media was created in early 2011 to continue the annual conference and develop  editorial content, including video journalism. Simone Ross, former program director for Fortune's conference division, served as program director for the initial Techonomy conference in 2010, and co-founded Techonomy Media as COO and Chief Program Officer for the company.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.forbes.com/people/simoneross/ | work=Forbes}}</ref> Michael Federle also was a co-founder of the company.<ref name=Folio>{{cite web|last=Kinsman|first=Matt|title=Forbes Media Makes Minority Investment in Startup of Ex-Fortune Editor|url=http://www.foliomag.com/2011/forbes-media-takes-minority-investment-startup-founded-ex-fortune-editors|publisher=Folio Mag|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> Forbes Media, which includes [[Forbes]] and Forbes.com, became a minority investor in the company in July 2011.<ref name=Folio /><ref>{{cite web | url= http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=138258679| title=Company Overview of Techonomy Media Inc.| publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek| accessdate=2013-07-09}}</ref>\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== Techonomy Flagship Conferences ===\n* 2010: [[Lake Tahoe]] in [[Truckee, California]]\n* 2011: [[Tucson]], [[Arizona]]\n** '''Revolutions in Progress''' \u2014 The growing mismatch between the desires and capabilities of technology-empowered individuals and the habits and practices of the institutions, corporations and governments that serve them.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.techpageone.com/uncategorized/seeing-the-world-through-the-lens-of-techonomy/#.Udx6nby9wcv| title=Seeing the World Through the Lens of Techonomy| publisher=Tech Page One of Dell| accessdate=2013-07-09}}</ref>\n* 2012: Tucson, Arizona\n** '''Insurgency and Opportunity: Companies, Countries, and Communities'''\n* 2013: Tucson, Arizona\n** '''The Business of Revolution'''\n* 2014: [[Half Moon Bay, California]]\n\n=== Techonomy Detroit ===\n* 2012: [[Detroit]]\n:Participants: [[Angela Benton]], [[Steve Case]], [[Jack Dorsey]], [[Timothy C. Draper]], [[Justin Fox]], [[Dan Gilbert (businessman)|Dan Gilbert]], [[Bruce J. Katz]], [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]], [[Vivek Kundra]], [[Josh Linkner]], [[Carlo Ratti]], [[Michael Teitelbaum]]\n* 2013: Detroit\n** '''Competitiveness, Jobs, and the Urban Future in an Age of Technology''' \u2014 The national challenge of inadequate and inequitable education.<ref name=\":0\" />\n:Participants: [[Jocelyn Benson]], [[Rodney Brooks]], [[Jean Case]], [[Emily Chang (journalist)|Emily Chang]], [[John Wm. Covington]], [[Jack Dorsey]], [[Keith Ferrazzi]], [[Dan Gilbert (businessman)|Dan Gilbert]], [[Bruce J. Katz]], [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]], [[Josh Linkner]], [[Edward Luce]], [[Larry Morrissey]], [[Marlin Page]], [[Hector Ruiz]], [[Rick Snyder]], [[M. Roy Wilson]]\n* 2014: Detroit\n:Participants: [[Jocelyn Benson]], [[Jean Case]], [[Susan P. Crawford]], [[Dickson Despommier]], [[Jack Dorsey]], [[Justin Fox]], [[Dan Gilbert (businessman)|Dan Gilbert]], [[Andrew Keen]], [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]], [[Josh Linkner]], [[Arun Sundararajan]], [[Philip D. Zelikow]]\n\n=== Techonomy Lab ===\n* 2013: [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]]\n** '''The Internet of Everything''' \u2014 Exploring and discussing the emerging Internet age in which software and apps begin to catch up with the loads of data that are produced and stored.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.crunchbase.com/company/techonomy-media| title=Techonomy| publisher=CrunchBase | accessdate=2013-07-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Techonomy Campus ===\n* 2013: [[Tel Aviv]]\n\n=== Techonomy Bio ===\n* 2015: [[Mountain View, California]]\n:Participants: [[Marc Benioff]], [[Walter De Brouwer]], [[Drew Endy]], [[Juan Enr\u00edquez]], [[David Kirkpatrick (author)|David Kirkpatrick]], [[Terry Sejnowski]]\n\n=== Techonomy Policy ===\n* 2015: [[Washington, DC]]\n:Participants: [[Cory Booker]],<ref name=\"offtheleash\">{{Cite news|url=http://offtheleash.net/2015/06/10/regulation-and-innovation/|title=Techonomy Policy Conference: Two Senators and a Geek Make the Case Against Regulation|publisher=Off the Leash|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> [[Julie Brill]], [[Steve Case]], [[Vint Cerf]], [[Fadi Chehade]], [